			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The sharing hate lists idea is interesting, and very different from how EQ works now. Let's use the example of a warrior and a cleric fighting two mobs...
<br />

<br />
Warrior is fighting Orc A and Orc B, and is actually attacking/taunting Orc A. Cleric heals Warrior. Now, since Warrior is attacking and taunting Orc A, Orc A stays on Warrior, but Orc B will attack the cleric, since her heal puts here on the hate list of Orc B, and the warrior has done nothing to raise himself on the hatelist of Orc B.
<br />

<br />
With your soultion...
<br />

<br />
Warrior is fighting Orc A and Orc B, and is actually attacking/taunting Orc A. However, since they share a hate list, it goes on as if he was attacking and taunting BOTH of the orcs. When Cleric heals Warrior, instead of Orc B attacking Cleric, both Orcs stay on Warrior, since he has been pushing himself higher and higher on the hatelist of Orcs (A and B).
<br />

<br />
A very interesting idea, and one I happen to like.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
